study funded by the National Cancer Institute, Cancer Therapeutics

27
00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:54.540
Evaluation Program, and conducted through the Experimental

28
00:01:54.620 --> 00:01:56.560
Therapeutics Clinical Trials Network.

29
00:01:59.020 --> 00:02:02.740
Topoisomerase 1 inhibitors trap topoisomerase 1

30
00:02:02.750 --> 00:02:06.700
during DNA cleavage, generating topoisomerase DNA

31
00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:10.301
cleavage complexes, also referred to as TOP1 cleavage

32
00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:11.120
complexes.

33
00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:15.560
The collision of replication forks and transcription complexes

34
00:02:15.940 --> 00:02:19.520
with TOP1 cleavage complexes generate irreversible

35
00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:22.940
cleavage complexes as cleaved DNA templates become

36
00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:26.340
misaligned. Subsequently, there's the generation of

37
00:02:26.380 --> 00:02:27.980
double-stranded DNA breaks.

38
00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:33.340
The repair of these cleavage complexes relies in part on PARP,

39
00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:37.180
which promotes replication fork reversal to prevent collisions,

40
00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:41.260
and via PARylation recruits TDP1 to

41
00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:43.160
excise these cleavage complexes.

42
00:02:44.940 --> 00:02:48.320
Therefore, PARP inhibition potentiates the DNA-damaging

43
00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:50.280
effects of TOP1 inhibition.

44
00:02:51.780 --> 00:02:55.489
Of note, synergy between PARP inhibitors and TOP1 inhibitors

45
00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:59.680
occurs due to PARP catalytic inhibition and is independent

46
00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:01.090
of PARP trapping ability.

47
00:03:04.040 --> 00:03:07.740
Multiple lines of pre-clinical evidence supports PARP inhibitor

48
00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:10.920
potentiation of TOP1 inhibitor-induced

49
00:03:11.060 --> 00:03:11.990
cytotoxicity.

50
00:03:12.980 --> 00:03:16.660
In clinical studies, however, substantial rates of hematologic

51
00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:20.390
toxicity, even when using a weak PARP trapper such as

52
00:03:20.420 --> 00:03:24.100
veliparib, offset by low rates of clinical activity,

53
00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:28.420
have limited combinations of PARP inhibitors with a classical

54
00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:30.430
TOP1 inhibiting chemotherapy.

55
00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:36.820
Therefore, we hypothesized that targeted delivery of a TOP1

56
00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:40.760
inhibitor via an antibody drug conjugate may reduce

57
00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:44.140
systemic toxicity and improve anti-tumor

58
00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:44.820
efficacy.

59
00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:49.560
We sought to evaluate this using DS-8201A, more

60
00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:53.340
commonly known as trastuzumab deruxtecan or T-DXd,

61
00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:57.720
which is a HER2-targeting ADC carrying a potent

62
00:03:57.760 --> 00:04:01.560
exatecan derivative TOP1 inhibiting payload with a

63
00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:04.080
drug antibody ratio of approximately eight.

64
00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:08.829
At the time of trial initiation, DS-8201A was

65
00:04:08.840 --> 00:04:12.660
only indicated for use in select breast and gastroesophageal

66
00:04:12.700 --> 00:04:13.260
cancers.

67
00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:18.340
We sought to combine DS-8201A with olaparib, a PARP

68
00:04:18.360 --> 00:04:22.120
inhibitor which was indicated only for select ovarian, breast,

69
00:04:22.460 --> 00:04:25.720
pancreatic, and prostate cancers at the time of study start.

70
00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:31.200
We sequentially explored three dosing schedules of

71
00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:35.140
olaparib with DS-8201A in three modules in dose

72
00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:39.040
escalation. This illustration depicts the rationale

73
00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:42.860
for gapped schedule olaparib dosing studied in two of the dose

74
00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:44.100
escalation modules.

75
00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:48.720
The rationale here is that after administration of a TOP1

76
00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:52.469
inhibitor, TOP1 cleavage complexes remain loaded in

77
00:04:52.580 --> 00:04:56.320
tumor cells, as depicted in the green areas under the curve,

78
00:04:57.020 --> 00:05:00.969
while they are cleared from normal tissues, as depicted in the red areas under the

79
00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:01.420
curve.

80
00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:06.300
Therefore, administration of a PARP inhibitor a few days after a

81
00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:10.080
TOP1 inhibitor may maximize tumor DNA damage

82
00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:12.560
while mitigating effects in normal tissues.

83
00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:17.740
However, as the optimal timing of PARP inhibition after TOP1

84
00:05:17.750 --> 00:05:21.620
inhibition is not yet known, we explored differing schedules

85
00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:23.180
in modules two and three.

86
00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:29.120
In this Phase 1 study, we began enrollment in module one,

87
00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:33.210
evaluating continuously dosed olaparib given days one through

88
00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:36.040
21 of each 21-day cycle of treatment.

89
00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:41.460
We subsequently explored gap schedule olaparib in module two, where

90
00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:43.600
it was dosed days eight through 14,

91
00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:48.520
and in module three, where olaparib was given days three through nine.

92
00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:54.900
We enrolled adult patients with HER2-positive advanced solid

93
00:05:54.940 --> 00:05:58.740
tumors, defined as those with HER2 IHC expression of

94
00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:02.440
one plus or greater, or ERBB2 amplification.

95
00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:07.204
Measurable disease per resist was requiredAt least one

96
00:06:07.304 --> 00:06:11.154
prior line of cytotoxic chemotherapy was required, though there

97
00:06:11.164 --> 00:06:14.394
was no upper limit on the total number of previous therapies.

98
00:06:15.544 --> 00:06:17.424
Prior PARP inhibitor use was allowed.

99
00:06:18.924 --> 00:06:22.634
The primary objectives of this study were to evaluate the safety and

100
00:06:22.724 --> 00:06:26.404
tolerability of combined DS-8201A and olaparib

101
00:06:26.844 --> 00:06:29.764
and to define and select the recommended Phase 2 dose.

102
00:06:31.224 --> 00:06:35.164
Secondary objectives included the evaluation of clinical activity of

103
00:06:35.204 --> 00:06:38.764
this combination as measured by the objective response rate,

104
00:06:39.344 --> 00:06:43.154
clinical benefit rate, duration of response, and progression-free

105
00:06:43.244 --> 00:06:44.864
survival.

106
00:06:46.664 --> 00:06:50.094
In dose escalation, 28 patients received study therapy.

107
00:06:50.704 --> 00:06:54.554
All were female with a median age of 64 years and had

108
00:06:54.644 --> 00:06:57.204
either endometrial cancer or ovarian cancer.

109
00:06:58.744 --> 00:07:02.344
These patients were heavily pre-treated, having received a median of

110
00:07:02.524 --> 00:07:06.194
3.5 prior lines of therapy and a range of one to 10

111
00:07:06.264 --> 00:07:07.044
prior lines.

112
00:07:08.644 --> 00:07:12.364
Over 40% of patients had previously received PARP inhibitors.

113
00:07:14.484 --> 00:07:18.104
The majority of patients had a platinum-free interval of less than six

114
00:07:18.144 --> 00:07:19.834
months at the time of study entry.

115
00:07:23.724 --> 00:07:26.644
43% of patients had endometrial cancer and

116
00:07:26.684 --> 00:07:28.844
57% had ovarian cancer.

117
00:07:29.674 --> 00:07:33.524
They were predominantly high-grade histologic subtypes, including

118
00:07:33.624 --> 00:07:37.564
uterine serous carcinoma and high-grade serous ovarian carcinoma.

119
00:07:39.604 --> 00:07:43.324
HER2 expression was required for eligibility, and local HER2

120
00:07:43.384 --> 00:07:47.344
testing results showed that the majority of patients had an expression of

121
00:07:47.484 --> 00:07:47.964
2+.

122
00:07:48.864 --> 00:07:52.734
Within this group of 2+ expressers was one patient who was concurrently

123
00:07:52.804 --> 00:07:56.704
reported as ERBB2 amplified and one patient for

124
00:07:56.744 --> 00:07:59.464
whom local testing had an ambivalent score of

125
00:07:59.664 --> 00:08:01.144
1+/2+.

126
00:08:03.584 --> 00:08:07.304
The majority of patients had wild-type BRCA by local germline

127
00:08:07.424 --> 00:08:08.564
and somatic testing.

128
00:08:11.244 --> 00:08:15.203
In Module 1, we evaluated continuously dosed olaparib in

129
00:08:15.264 --> 00:08:17.624
a 3+3 dose escalation design.

130
00:08:18.484 --> 00:08:21.244
Patients were enrolled beginning at dose level one, in which

131
00:08:21.304 --> 00:08:24.784
DS-8201A was dosed at 4.4 milligrams per

132
00:08:24.844 --> 00:08:28.724
kilogram with olaparib 100 milligrams twice daily given

133
00:08:28.744 --> 00:08:29.933
days one through 21.

134
00:08:31.684 --> 00:08:35.524
Only one DLT was observed during the six-week DLT period,

135
00:08:36.345 --> 00:08:38.644
and escalation to dose level two was allowed.

136
00:08:39.544 --> 00:08:43.324
Here, DS-8201A was increased to 5.4 milligrams per

137
00:08:43.384 --> 00:08:47.354
kilogram while olaparib remained at 100 milligrams days one through

138
00:08:47.384 --> 00:08:47.933
21.

139
00:08:49.524 --> 00:08:53.354
Enrollment halted at this dose level due to three patients experiencing

140
00:08:53.384 --> 00:08:54.084
DLTs.

141
00:08:55.044 --> 00:08:57.224
All DLTs were hematologic in nature.

142
00:08:58.204 --> 00:09:02.124
Given this, Module 1 was declared infeasible and further enrollment to this

143
00:09:02.164 --> 00:09:03.144
module was halted.

144
00:09:05.444 --> 00:09:09.224
We subsequently evaluated seven days of gap schedule olaparib in

145
00:09:09.244 --> 00:09:12.944
Module 2, again via a 3+3 dose escalation

146
00:09:13.004 --> 00:09:13.484
design.

147
00:09:14.444 --> 00:09:17.564
At dose level one, we evaluated DS-8201A

148
00:09:17.844 --> 00:09:21.364
5.4 milligrams per kilogram with olaparib 100

149
00:09:21.404 --> 00:09:24.773
milligrams twice daily, now given days eight through 14.

150
00:09:25.744 --> 00:09:29.484
At this dose level, no DLTs were observed, allowing escalation to

151
00:09:29.544 --> 00:09:33.124
dose level two, where olaparib was increased to 200

152
00:09:33.164 --> 00:09:37.004
milligrams twice daily. And again, no DLTs were observed.

153
00:09:38.544 --> 00:09:42.344
Escalation to the highest planned dose level was achieved, where olaparib was

154
00:09:42.404 --> 00:09:46.384
increased again to 300 milligrams twice daily, days eight through 14.

155
00:09:47.344 --> 00:09:51.204
Only one DLT was observed, and overall, Module 2 was

156
00:09:51.244 --> 00:09:52.104
declared feasible.

157
00:09:54.624 --> 00:09:58.524
We sought to investigate alternative timing of gap schedule olaparib in

158
00:09:58.584 --> 00:10:02.493
Module 3. This module was designed as a single-dose level

159
00:10:02.604 --> 00:10:06.284
cohort where DS-8201A was given at

160
00:10:06.304 --> 00:10:09.864
5.4 milligrams per kilogram and olaparib at 300

161
00:10:09.904 --> 00:10:13.204
milligrams twice daily, now given days three through nine.

162
00:10:14.724 --> 00:10:18.414
Two patients experienced DLTs, halting further enrollment to this

163
00:10:18.464 --> 00:10:20.524
module, which was declared infeasible.

164
00:10:22.644 --> 00:10:26.424
Ultimately, the Module 2 regimen was selected as the recommended Phase 2

165
00:10:26.484 --> 00:10:30.284
dose. DS-8201A 5.4 milligrams per

166
00:10:30.344 --> 00:10:33.904
kilogram given once every three weeks with olaparib 300

167
00:10:33.944 --> 00:10:37.824
milligrams twice daily given days eight through 14 was

168
00:10:37.864 --> 00:10:41.694
selected for further investigation in the ongoing dose expansion

169
00:10:41.804 --> 00:10:42.284
cohort.

170
00:10:44.684 --> 00:10:48.104
Treatment-related adverse events were attenuated with gap schedule

171
00:10:48.124 --> 00:10:51.264
olaparib compared to continuously dosed olaparib.

172
00:10:52.104 --> 00:10:55.834
As shown here, treatment-related AEs were primarily hematologic

173
00:10:56.144 --> 00:10:59.984
with low-grade gastrointestinal toxicities consistent with the

174
00:11:00.024 --> 00:11:02.384
expected safety profile of both agents.

175
00:11:04.864 --> 00:11:08.394
Of note, hematologic AEs were markedly attenuated in

176
00:11:08.444 --> 00:11:12.294
Module 2 with gap schedule olaparib compared to Module 1.

177
00:11:13.344 --> 00:11:16.624
As seen here, reduced frequencies of Grade 3 and Grade 4

178
00:11:16.744 --> 00:11:20.244
neutropenia, anemia, and thrombocytopenia was

179
00:11:20.284 --> 00:11:22.324
observed with gap schedule olaparib.

180
00:11:24.984 --> 00:11:27.924
Pneumonitis was observed in patients enrolled to this study.

181
00:11:28.924 --> 00:11:32.864
This was in keeping and consistent with the expected safety profile of these

182
00:11:32.924 --> 00:11:34.524
agents and real-world reports.

183
00:11:35.584 --> 00:11:39.064
All pneumonitis events were low grade and occurred across dosing

184
00:11:39.144 --> 00:11:42.344
schedules, tumor types, and levels of HER2 expression.

185
00:11:43.804 --> 00:11:46.604
The majority of events occurred in later treatment cycles,

186
00:11:47.544 --> 00:11:50.304
and none occurred during the six-week DLT period.

187
00:11:52.704 --> 00:11:56.574
As shown in this waterfall plot, deep tumor reductions were seen with

188
00:11:56.604 --> 00:12:00.234
combined DS-8201A and olaparib. There was

189
00:12:00.264 --> 00:12:03.984
encouraging evidence of anti-tumor efficacy with an objective

190
00:12:04.004 --> 00:12:05.984
response rate of 54%

191
00:12:06.924 --> 00:12:10.714
and a confirmed ORR of 46%. This includes a

192
00:12:10.744 --> 00:12:14.044
confirmed complete response and 12 confirmed partial

193
00:12:14.064 --> 00:12:17.698
responses.The confirmed clinical benefit rate was

194
00:12:17.908 --> 00:12:21.457
67%, and the median duration of response was

195
00:12:21.508 --> 00:12:22.778
11.2 months.

196
00:12:23.848 --> 00:12:27.808
Responses were observed in both endometrial and ovarian cancer patients

197
00:12:28.288 --> 00:12:31.908
across levels of HER2 expression and in patients who had

198
00:12:31.948 --> 00:12:35.598
previously received PARP inhibitors and anti-HER2 agents.

199
00:12:37.888 --> 00:12:41.658
As shown in the swimmer plot, durable disease control was also seen with

200
00:12:41.668 --> 00:12:43.768
DS-8201A and olaparib.

201
00:12:45.338 --> 00:12:48.508
This was seen across modules with a median duration of treatment of

202
00:12:48.527 --> 00:12:50.068
36.1 weeks.

203
00:12:51.228 --> 00:12:55.188
With a median follow-up of 8.4 months, 19 patients

204
00:12:55.248 --> 00:12:57.378
were alive and progression-free at six months.

205
00:12:58.368 --> 00:13:02.228
The six-month PFS was estimated at 88.2%

206
00:13:03.328 --> 00:13:07.068
and the median progression-free survival was estimated at 15.2

207
00:13:07.108 --> 00:13:07.438
months.

208
00:13:10.268 --> 00:13:14.128
Clinical activity of combined DS-8201A and olaparib

209
00:13:14.168 --> 00:13:16.568
was observed even in HER2 low settings.

210
00:13:17.148 --> 00:13:21.048
For example, a confirmed partial response was observed in a patient with

211
00:13:21.088 --> 00:13:25.068
HER2 IHC 1+ primary platinum-refractory clear

212
00:13:25.148 --> 00:13:28.928
cell ovarian carcinoma, a subtype of ovarian cancer

213
00:13:28.948 --> 00:13:32.448
historically considered to be chemotherapy-resistant.

214
00:13:32.458 --> 00:13:35.958
This patient was heavily pretreated, having received carboplatin and

215
00:13:35.988 --> 00:13:38.808
paclitaxel, palbociclib/gadadoliseib,

216
00:13:39.368 --> 00:13:42.108
ipilimumab, nivolumab, and gemcitabine.

217
00:13:42.948 --> 00:13:46.548
As shown here, there was marked reduction in size of a large omental

218
00:13:46.608 --> 00:13:46.948
mass.

219
00:13:49.068 --> 00:13:52.838
Similarly, a confirmed partial response was also seen in a patient with

220
00:13:52.888 --> 00:13:56.268
HER2 IHC 1+ primary platinum-resistant

221
00:13:56.648 --> 00:13:58.568
high-grade serous ovarian carcinoma.

222
00:13:59.488 --> 00:14:03.028
This patient was also heavily pretreated and had PARP inhibitor-resistant

223
00:14:03.108 --> 00:14:06.758
disease. As shown here, there was substantial shrinkage in the

224
00:14:06.808 --> 00:14:07.848
peritoneal mass.

225
00:14:10.408 --> 00:14:13.048
In conclusion, gapped schedule olaparib with

226
00:14:13.088 --> 00:14:16.488
DS-8201A demonstrated an acceptable safety

227
00:14:16.588 --> 00:14:17.168
profile.

228
00:14:18.068 --> 00:14:21.948
Pneumonitis events were observed but were all low grade in seven patients.

229
00:14:23.048 --> 00:14:26.908
DS-8201A 5.4 milligrams per kilogram given once

230
00:14:26.968 --> 00:14:30.608
every three weeks, with olaparib 300 milligrams twice daily

231
00:14:30.788 --> 00:14:34.628
given days eight through 14, was selected as the recommended Phase II

232
00:14:34.708 --> 00:14:35.048
dose.

233
00:14:36.228 --> 00:14:39.908
There was evidence of clinical activity across dose escalation modules,

234
00:14:40.368 --> 00:14:44.088
tumor types, and levels of HER2 expression, including

235
00:14:44.108 --> 00:14:46.808
those with HER2 IHC 1+ expression.

236
00:14:47.848 --> 00:14:51.768
Fifty-four percent of patients demonstrated an objective response with a

237
00:14:51.808 --> 00:14:53.928
confirmed ORR of 46%.

238
00:14:54.928 --> 00:14:58.388
Nineteen patients were alive and progression-free at six months,

239
00:14:58.888 --> 00:15:02.728
and the six-month PFS was estimated at 88.2%.

240
00:15:03.628 --> 00:15:07.368
The median PFS was estimated at 15.2 months.

241
00:15:08.428 --> 00:15:12.188
Based on these results from dose escalation, enrollment is ongoing

242
00:15:12.548 --> 00:15:16.228
in a HER2 IHC 1+ platinum-resistant ovarian

243
00:15:16.348 --> 00:15:18.228
cancer dose expansion cohort.

244
00:15:20.248 --> 00:15:23.948
On behalf of my co-authors, I would like to thank the patients, their families and

245
00:15:23.968 --> 00:15:27.317
caregivers, and all investigators and study staff involved in this

246
00:15:27.348 --> 00:15:30.968
trial. Sincere thank you to Dr. Cheryl Pickett, who has been an

247
00:15:31.008 --> 00:15:34.948
incredible champion of this study, and the staff at the NCI and CTAC.

248
00:15:35.708 --> 00:15:39.418
Thank you to Daiichi Sankyo, AstraZeneca, and the Luen Foundation to Fight Women's

249
00:15:39.508 --> 00:15:39.968
Cancers.

250
00:15:48.608 --> 00:15:49.548
Thank you very much.

251
00:15:50.708 --> 00:15:54.448
The next presenter is the discussant for this

252
00:15:54.468 --> 00:15:58.368
presentation, Dr. Aditya Bardia from UCLA.

253
00:16:04.988 --> 00:16:05.628
Good afternoon.

254
00:16:07.048 --> 00:16:10.828
Thank you, co-chairs. Thank you, organizers. Thanks to Dr.

255
00:16:10.868 --> 00:16:14.268
Linian Xu for inviting me as a discussant.

256
00:16:15.308 --> 00:16:18.958
Excellent presentation by Dr. Li and team, and congrats to them for

257
00:16:19.028 --> 00:16:20.648
conducting this important study.

258
00:16:21.488 --> 00:16:25.258
It sets the stage for ADC-based combination

259
00:16:25.328 --> 00:16:27.128
therapy, the next wave.

260
00:16:29.568 --> 00:16:31.568
These are my financial disclosures.

261
00:16:34.888 --> 00:16:36.568
So I'll review three things today.

262
00:16:36.608 --> 00:16:40.568
I'll talk about work done in the field, what we've learned today,

263
00:16:40.648 --> 00:16:42.677
as well as where the field is going.

264
00:16:46.808 --> 00:16:50.408
Antibody drug conjugates essentially allow for selective

265
00:16:50.448 --> 00:16:52.237
delivery of toxic payload.

266
00:16:53.178 --> 00:16:56.428
The first step is binding of the ADC to the antigen.

267
00:16:57.068 --> 00:17:00.548
The next step is internalization to form an early

268
00:17:00.608 --> 00:17:04.588
endosome. Third is degradation of the ADC in

269
00:17:04.608 --> 00:17:05.398
the lysosome.

270
00:17:06.288 --> 00:17:08.459
Fourth is release of the payload,

271
00:17:09.288 --> 00:17:13.068
and five, the payload exerting its effect

272
00:17:13.128 --> 00:17:16.748
resulting in apoptosis. This has been the traditional

273
00:17:16.788 --> 00:17:20.328
mechanism for an ADC. But newer

274
00:17:20.408 --> 00:17:24.168
ADCs also have a bystander effect,

275
00:17:24.668 --> 00:17:28.168
and this has been a game changer in the field of oncology

276
00:17:28.568 --> 00:17:32.188
because it can address antigen heterogeneity

277
00:17:32.688 --> 00:17:36.398
and can also allow ADCs to work in tumors that

278
00:17:36.428 --> 00:17:38.988
have low expression of the antigen.

279
00:17:40.138 --> 00:17:43.748
A poster child of this is trastuzumab deruxtecan, or

280
00:17:43.768 --> 00:17:47.568
T-DXd. It has shown not only activity in

281
00:17:47.608 --> 00:17:51.558
breast cancer that has high expression of HER2, but

282
00:17:51.648 --> 00:17:55.588
also activity in tumors that have low expression of

283
00:17:55.688 --> 00:17:59.268
HER2, including ultra-low HER2 positive breast

284
00:17:59.348 --> 00:17:59.888
cancer.

285
00:18:01.668 --> 00:18:05.448
Besides activity in breast cancer, T-DXd

286
00:18:05.508 --> 00:18:08.648
has also demonstrated activity in other

287
00:18:08.868 --> 00:18:12.648
HER2-expressing solid tumors, endometrial cancer,

288
00:18:12.788 --> 00:18:16.772
cervical cancer, ovarian cancer, bladder cancer.And

289
00:18:16.832 --> 00:18:20.321
indeed, in April of 2024,

290
00:18:20.932 --> 00:18:24.602
the FDA approved trastuzumab deruxtecan, or

291
00:18:24.792 --> 00:18:28.412
T-DXd, for patients who have solid

292
00:18:28.512 --> 00:18:32.042
tumors that express HER2, or HER2-expressing

293
00:18:32.412 --> 00:18:34.832
solid tumors. This is the first

294
00:18:35.532 --> 00:18:38.872
tumor-agnostic approval of an ADC.

295
00:18:41.052 --> 00:18:44.752
So now the question is: how can we improve the outcomes

296
00:18:44.872 --> 00:18:48.592
further? How can we build combinations with

297
00:18:48.652 --> 00:18:49.332
ADC?

298
00:18:51.952 --> 00:18:55.172
In principle, one could develop

299
00:18:55.372 --> 00:18:58.552
mechanistic combinations based on the payload.

300
00:18:58.592 --> 00:19:02.302
So ADCs have a payload. Looking at the mechanism of the

301
00:19:02.432 --> 00:19:06.352
payload, you can combine the ADC with a targeted

302
00:19:06.392 --> 00:19:09.632
therapy. Let's talk about T-DXd

303
00:19:10.112 --> 00:19:13.932
or other ADCs that have a TOP1 payload, such

304
00:19:13.972 --> 00:19:17.692
as sacituzumab govitecan, datopotamab deruxtecan.

305
00:19:17.812 --> 00:19:20.812
All of these have TOP1 inhibitors as the payload.

306
00:19:21.392 --> 00:19:25.212
The TOP1 inhibitor is delivered to the cancer cell.

307
00:19:25.852 --> 00:19:29.232
This results in the formation of TOP1cc's,

308
00:19:29.892 --> 00:19:33.252
which are cleared by PARP. So potentially,

309
00:19:33.572 --> 00:19:37.312
combining these drugs with a PARP inhibitor would

310
00:19:37.432 --> 00:19:38.992
make mechanistic sense.

311
00:19:40.182 --> 00:19:42.832
The challenge is overlapping toxicity.

312
00:19:43.552 --> 00:19:47.512
Many of these ADCs cause myelosuppression, and

313
00:19:47.552 --> 00:19:50.452
PARP inhibitors cause myelosuppression as well.

314
00:19:52.172 --> 00:19:56.092
Indeed, in the past, when chemotherapy was combined with

315
00:19:56.152 --> 00:19:57.112
PARP inhibitors,

316
00:19:58.072 --> 00:20:01.972
it was very challenging to combine these drugs in clinic,

317
00:20:02.452 --> 00:20:06.412
and the development of multiple combinations, irinotecan,

318
00:20:06.512 --> 00:20:10.032
topotecan, with olaparib were discontinued.

319
00:20:10.212 --> 00:20:14.062
In principle, it made sense. Irinotecan, topotecan, those are

320
00:20:14.092 --> 00:20:17.722
TOP1 inhibitors, and combining that with a PARP inhibitor in

321
00:20:17.732 --> 00:20:19.892
preclinical models showed synergy.

322
00:20:20.392 --> 00:20:24.372
But in the clinic, the combination, because of toxicity, was very

323
00:20:24.412 --> 00:20:25.531
difficult to develop.

324
00:20:26.612 --> 00:20:28.732
But this changes with ADCs.

325
00:20:29.932 --> 00:20:31.372
As was mentioned by Dr. Lee,

326
00:20:32.412 --> 00:20:35.892
with an ADC, you have higher delivery of the

327
00:20:35.932 --> 00:20:38.272
payload in the tumor microenvironment.

328
00:20:39.302 --> 00:20:43.162
The payload is then cleared from normal cells, but because you have

329
00:20:43.252 --> 00:20:47.212
higher delivery of the payload in the tumor microenvironment, it stays

330
00:20:47.252 --> 00:20:51.152
there for a longer period of time. So if you wait for a few

331
00:20:51.192 --> 00:20:54.772
days, you could potentially then add the PARP

332
00:20:54.812 --> 00:20:58.472
inhibitor. So you give the ADC, wait for a few days, add the

333
00:20:58.592 --> 00:21:02.472
PARP inhibitor. The payload is still in the tumor microenvironment,

334
00:21:02.572 --> 00:21:06.132
so in the tumor microenvironment, the PARP inhibitor would

335
00:21:06.192 --> 00:21:07.342
exert synergy.

336
00:21:09.392 --> 00:21:13.372
Our team presented initial results at ACR a few years

337
00:21:13.432 --> 00:21:17.112
ago where we asked this question of combining an ADC,

338
00:21:17.292 --> 00:21:21.232
sacituzumab govitecan, that has a TOP1 inhibitor payload

339
00:21:21.652 --> 00:21:25.152
with a PARP inhibitor. And the question was: will give them together

340
00:21:25.752 --> 00:21:29.692
versus using a staggered schedule where SG is given

341
00:21:29.792 --> 00:21:33.772
day one, day eight, every 21 days, and then the PARP inhibitor is

342
00:21:33.872 --> 00:21:37.632
given in the off week. This was a translational study.

343
00:21:39.152 --> 00:21:42.572
In the preclinical setting, the team had seen that in cell

344
00:21:42.612 --> 00:21:46.432
lines, if you give SG and then wait for some

345
00:21:46.472 --> 00:21:50.332
time and then add the PARP inhibitor, you see

346
00:21:50.372 --> 00:21:54.172
higher synergy as compared to single agent, and you also

347
00:21:54.332 --> 00:21:58.212
see that TOP1cc's are stabilized by using

348
00:21:58.252 --> 00:22:01.872
the PARP inhibitor. Just giving SG alone, TOP1cc's are

349
00:22:01.952 --> 00:22:05.842
cleared, but if you wait and then add the PARP inhibitor, you

350
00:22:05.932 --> 00:22:09.572
see stabilization of TOP1cc's. So this was in the

351
00:22:09.592 --> 00:22:13.572
preclinical setting. To test this hypothesis, looked at the

352
00:22:13.612 --> 00:22:16.592
combination of the ADC with a PARP

353
00:22:16.632 --> 00:22:20.412
inhibitor. Giving them together was too toxic.

354
00:22:20.732 --> 00:22:24.392
With the concurrent schedule, 71% of patients had

355
00:22:24.452 --> 00:22:28.372
DLT. But if you use a staggered schedule, none of

356
00:22:28.412 --> 00:22:32.262
the patients had DLT. So the next question is: was this

357
00:22:32.272 --> 00:22:34.452
combination active? And it was active.

358
00:22:34.952 --> 00:22:38.921
With the concurrent schedule, it was very difficult to give that, but with

359
00:22:38.952 --> 00:22:42.832
the staggered schedule, you could give both the ADC and

360
00:22:42.872 --> 00:22:46.432
the PARP inhibitor, and you saw responses with this

361
00:22:46.452 --> 00:22:47.252
combination.

362
00:22:48.812 --> 00:22:52.712
At this meeting, now we've seen results related to T-DXd

363
00:22:52.872 --> 00:22:55.092
plus olaparib. The team

364
00:22:56.212 --> 00:23:00.092
looked at the combination in a continuous schedule, giving both these

365
00:23:00.172 --> 00:23:03.672
drugs together, as well as this gap or staggered schedule

366
00:23:04.052 --> 00:23:07.532
where T-DXd was given, and then on day eight to

367
00:23:07.632 --> 00:23:11.152
14, olaparib was given. T-DXd is given every

368
00:23:11.352 --> 00:23:15.192
21 days, so this allowed them to give the ADC,

369
00:23:15.332 --> 00:23:18.192
wait for a few days, and then add the PARP inhibitor.

370
00:23:19.432 --> 00:23:22.592
As was mentioned, giving them together was too toxic.

371
00:23:22.692 --> 00:23:25.842
That was not feasible. But the staggered

372
00:23:26.012 --> 00:23:29.772
schedule was still feasible, giving T-DXd followed by

373
00:23:29.792 --> 00:23:30.492
olaparib.

374
00:23:32.292 --> 00:23:36.282
And the advantage of the staggered schedule was that the side effects

375
00:23:36.672 --> 00:23:40.372
were decreased, be it myelosuppression, be

376
00:23:40.532 --> 00:23:44.352
it diarrhea, that was lower by giving

377
00:23:44.392 --> 00:23:47.732
these drugs in a staggered fashion, and that's the principle or the

378
00:23:47.772 --> 00:23:50.522
advantage of using these drugs in this sequence.

379
00:23:51.452 --> 00:23:54.912
More importantly, the clinical activity was maintained.

380
00:23:54.952 --> 00:23:56.282
You could see responses,

381
00:23:57.632 --> 00:24:01.362
a partial response, as well as confirmed response by

382
00:24:01.432 --> 00:24:04.102
using the ADC along with the PARP inhibitor.

383
00:24:04.712 --> 00:24:08.352
Overall response rate of 54%. So the team

384
00:24:08.432 --> 00:24:12.371
provided very important proof of principle that you can give these

385
00:24:12.392 --> 00:24:15.592
drugs together. You just have to use them in a staggered

386
00:24:15.652 --> 00:24:19.632
schedule.So the next question is

387
00:24:19.952 --> 00:24:21.972
the elephant in the room, which is:

388
00:24:22.792 --> 00:24:25.912
What does the combination add to monotherapy?

389
00:24:26.612 --> 00:24:30.232
Is the activity of T-DXd plus olaparib

390
00:24:30.312 --> 00:24:32.392
better than T-DXd alone?

391
00:24:33.852 --> 00:24:37.712
If we look at the results of DESTINY-PanTumor-02, that

392
00:24:37.752 --> 00:24:41.592
was a clinical trial that looked at T-DXd as a single agent

393
00:24:41.692 --> 00:24:42.432
monotherapy.

394
00:24:43.292 --> 00:24:47.032
In that trial, in endometrial carcinoma, the response

395
00:24:47.112 --> 00:24:50.902
rate was 57.5%; in ovarian cancer, it

396
00:24:50.932 --> 00:24:52.232
was 45%.

397
00:24:53.452 --> 00:24:56.852
Now, I would caution with cross-trial comparisons between

398
00:24:56.912 --> 00:24:59.292
DESTINY-PanTumor-02 and this study.

399
00:24:59.852 --> 00:25:03.722
I think what we need is a step forward, which would be a randomized

400
00:25:03.772 --> 00:25:07.292
study for patients with HER2-expressing advanced

401
00:25:07.412 --> 00:25:09.052
platinum-resistant ovarian

402
00:25:09.872 --> 00:25:13.772
and/or endometrial carcinoma, looking at T-DXd as a

403
00:25:13.852 --> 00:25:17.292
single agent versus T-DXd plus a PARP

404
00:25:17.312 --> 00:25:19.512
inhibitor in the staggered schedule.

405
00:25:20.042 --> 00:25:23.912
Patients would receive the drug, and then you can really ask the question

406
00:25:23.952 --> 00:25:27.272
of clinical activity of combination versus single agent.

407
00:25:27.312 --> 00:25:30.952
You can look at PFS, OS response rate, as well as safety.

408
00:25:31.912 --> 00:25:35.672
Now, as the trial is being designed, we need to consider a few things.

409
00:25:36.752 --> 00:25:38.702
The first is biomarker selection.

410
00:25:39.292 --> 00:25:43.172
Should this be a biomarker-driven study where

411
00:25:43.252 --> 00:25:46.842
only patients with a certain biomarker that are more likely to respond from

412
00:25:46.852 --> 00:25:50.632
combination are included, or does this become biomarker-enriched?

413
00:25:51.392 --> 00:25:53.272
What are the stratification factors?

414
00:25:53.832 --> 00:25:57.492
HER2 IHC 1+ versus 2+? Should you

415
00:25:57.592 --> 00:26:01.152
also include HER2 ultra low, that is HER2

416
00:26:01.232 --> 00:26:04.592
0+? And finally, the field has evolved.

417
00:26:04.632 --> 00:26:07.352
Now we have PARP1 selective inhibitors.

418
00:26:07.762 --> 00:26:11.672
So should the combination be with a PARP1 selective inhibitor,

419
00:26:11.712 --> 00:26:13.812
which might have even lower toxicity?

420
00:26:15.372 --> 00:26:19.152
So this is exciting and this is important because we are in an

421
00:26:19.212 --> 00:26:22.372
ADC revolution. There's a growing number of

422
00:26:22.432 --> 00:26:24.752
approvals in different cancers

423
00:26:25.792 --> 00:26:29.452
and more than 100 ADC in clinical development across

424
00:26:29.532 --> 00:26:33.272
tumors. The field is moving towards TOP1

425
00:26:33.332 --> 00:26:34.672
inhibitor payloads.

426
00:26:35.992 --> 00:26:39.392
Just last week at the annual meeting of women's cancer

427
00:26:39.572 --> 00:26:43.372
SGO, we saw results of trastuzumab pirmatucan,

428
00:26:43.912 --> 00:26:47.632
which showed a clinical activity of 50% in patients with

429
00:26:47.732 --> 00:26:49.572
metastatic endometrial carcinoma.

430
00:26:50.252 --> 00:26:54.092
At the same meeting, we saw sofimipitcan, another

431
00:26:54.152 --> 00:26:57.772
ADC with a TOP1 inhibitor payload targeting folate

432
00:26:57.812 --> 00:27:00.912
receptor, response rate close to 50%.

433
00:27:01.312 --> 00:27:05.152
And in the same meeting, a third ADC, Morez, for

434
00:27:05.252 --> 00:27:09.192
patients with metastatic endometrial ovarian carcinoma, another ADC

435
00:27:09.252 --> 00:27:13.112
with a TOP1 inhibitor payload, response rate of 62%.

436
00:27:13.852 --> 00:27:17.512
And with all these ADCs, potentially there's an opportunity of

437
00:27:17.592 --> 00:27:20.132
combining them with a PARP inhibitor.

438
00:27:21.512 --> 00:27:25.192
And that's just PARP inhibitor. Potentially, these drugs can

439
00:27:25.292 --> 00:27:29.212
also be combined with other DDR agents, ATR,

440
00:27:29.392 --> 00:27:33.112
CHEK, WEE1. So in the past, the combinations

441
00:27:33.212 --> 00:27:36.772
of chemo with these drugs were abandoned, but now is the

442
00:27:36.832 --> 00:27:40.301
opportunity of revisiting these combinations with

443
00:27:40.372 --> 00:27:41.152
ADCs.

444
00:27:42.212 --> 00:27:46.052
And that's just DDR agents. Potentially, these drugs can also

445
00:27:46.152 --> 00:27:49.612
be combined with immunotherapy. When there is apoptosis, there's

446
00:27:49.622 --> 00:27:53.342
activation in the tumor microenvironment, the immune cells,

447
00:27:53.492 --> 00:27:57.372
T-cells that infiltrate with PD-1, PD-L1

448
00:27:57.432 --> 00:28:01.262
that can be blocked. So if you use a PD-L1 inhibitor with ADCs,

449
00:28:01.732 --> 00:28:05.512
with or without a PARP inhibitor, that could be synergistic, or

450
00:28:05.892 --> 00:28:09.472
developing ADCs with bispecific payloads.

451
00:28:11.092 --> 00:28:14.672
So in conclusion, ADCs have demonstrated

452
00:28:14.792 --> 00:28:18.732
superior activity to chemo in various solid tumors, and there

453
00:28:18.752 --> 00:28:21.052
are more than 100 in clinical development.

454
00:28:21.772 --> 00:28:25.172
This tumor-selective payload delivery may

455
00:28:25.352 --> 00:28:28.912
enable innovative drug scheduling to expand the

456
00:28:28.932 --> 00:28:32.552
therapeutic window, such as combination with a TOP1

457
00:28:32.612 --> 00:28:35.232
inhibitor payload with a PARP inhibitor.

458
00:28:35.861 --> 00:28:39.642
This study and other studies have provided proof of principle, and

459
00:28:39.692 --> 00:28:41.602
this merits additional evaluation.

460
00:28:42.512 --> 00:28:45.692
There's also the opportunity of revisiting combinations with

461
00:28:45.952 --> 00:28:49.872
other DDR agents. And overall as a field, we

462
00:28:49.912 --> 00:28:53.252
need translational investigation of mechanistic

463
00:28:53.372 --> 00:28:57.142
synergy related to ADC target payload processing

464
00:28:57.192 --> 00:29:00.772
mechanism, and that would help us develop rational

465
00:29:00.852 --> 00:29:03.932
ADC-based combinations. Thank you so much for your attention.

466
00:29:10.162 --> 00:29:12.812
I believe we have time for one question.

467
00:29:18.092 --> 00:29:18.692
Questions?

468
00:29:20.992 --> 00:29:23.592
If not, I have a couple of questions.

469
00:29:23.692 --> 00:29:27.592
I was wondering, I saw that several patients had

470
00:29:27.612 --> 00:29:31.572
prior PARP, so I was wondering about the tolerability

471
00:29:32.032 --> 00:29:35.812
of this combination in those patients, and also if you

472
00:29:35.892 --> 00:29:39.592
considered selecting for patients who are BRCA

473
00:29:39.652 --> 00:29:40.292
mutant.

474
00:29:41.332 --> 00:29:43.132
I think just one patient was

475
00:29:44.592 --> 00:29:46.372
BRCA mutant in your trial.

476
00:29:47.572 --> 00:29:49.892
Yeah. So there were two patients who were BRCA mutants.

477
00:29:49.932 --> 00:29:53.902
There was one patient who had a germline BRCA2 mutation and one patient with

478
00:29:53.932 --> 00:29:57.612
a somatic BRCA1 mutation. We haven't looked specifically at the

479
00:29:57.652 --> 00:30:01.512
tolerability of this combination in patients who have previously

480
00:30:01.552 --> 00:30:05.372
received PARP inhibitors. But I do want to highlight again that the

481
00:30:05.392 --> 00:30:08.952
dosing of the PARP inhibitor used, olaparib at 100 milligrams

482
00:30:09.332 --> 00:30:12.692
dosed just for seven days, is below the

483
00:30:12.712 --> 00:30:16.492
therapeutic dose that we would expect with a PARP inhibitor on its own

484
00:30:17.232 --> 00:30:20.372
where typically the minimum dose is 100 milligrams twice daily

485
00:30:20.432 --> 00:30:21.252
continuously.

486
00:30:22.212 --> 00:30:24.792
And with that dosing, it is fairly tolerable.

487
00:30:28.800 --> 00:30:29.980
Any other questions?

488
00:30:34.660 --> 00:30:34.940
Yes.

489
00:30:37.180 --> 00:30:40.220
So you showed that there were seven cases of pneumonia.

490
00:30:40.640 --> 00:30:43.860
Do you think that the combination may actually exacerbate

491
00:30:43.940 --> 00:30:45.600
the lung toxicity?

492
00:30:46.720 --> 00:30:50.420
That's a great question, and I think we're realizing that ILD and the risk of

493
00:30:50.460 --> 00:30:54.260
pneumonitis, with ADCs really is something we have to be

494
00:30:54.300 --> 00:30:55.440
vigilant for,

495
00:30:56.280 --> 00:31:00.040
and that we may be seeing higher rates in real-world experience

496
00:31:00.080 --> 00:31:02.460
compared to what's been reported in clinical trials.

497
00:31:02.980 --> 00:31:05.620
I think historically when we were starting to use

498
00:31:05.700 --> 00:31:09.420
DS-8021A-T-DXd in our studies, we were

499
00:31:09.440 --> 00:31:11.920
anticipating a rate of approximately 10%.

500
00:31:12.320 --> 00:31:16.200
But as we're seeing more real-world reports emerge, really that's higher

